## 🔎 Minor Findings (Not Blockers)

### 1. [config/schema.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/config/schema.py) is a stub — not wired in

[schema.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/config/schema.py) defines [RuntimeConfig](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/config/schema.py#6-11), [ProviderConfig](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/config/schema.py#13-20), [SelfDeployConfig](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/config/schema.py#22-25) Pydantic models, but nothing imports or uses them. The actual settings come from [backend/settings.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/settings.py) which uses a `@dataclass`. Two config systems = future confusion.

> **Fix (Phase 2):** Choose one. Either promote [schema.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/config/schema.py) to be the canonical config and have [settings.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/settings.py) load into it, or delete [schema.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/config/schema.py) and add Pydantic validation to [settings.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/settings.py).

### 2. `huggingface_hub` in [requirements-server.txt](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/requirements-server.txt) — conditional dependency

The server-only requirements include `huggingface_hub` which is ~50MB installed. If someone runs `PERSISTENCE_MODE=local`, they never need it. Not a blocker but matters for Docker image size.

> **Fix:** Make it optional — lazy-import in [persistence.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/persistence.py) (already does `from huggingface_hub import HfApi` lazily ✅), but pip will still install it eagerly. Consider moving it to an extras group: `pip install .[hf]`.

### 3. [postprocessing.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/postprocessing.py) imports [parse_mcp_result](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/activity.py#28-44) from [activity.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/activity.py)

This creates a **circular dependency risk**: [activity.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/activity.py) defines [parse_mcp_result](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/activity.py#28-44) (a pure utility), [postprocessing.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/postprocessing.py) depends on it, and [server.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/server.py) imports both. Currently works because Python resolves at function-call time. But if [activity.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/activity.py) ever imports from [postprocessing.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/postprocessing.py), it'll break.

> **Fix:** Extract [parse_mcp_result](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/activity.py#28-44) to a tiny `utils.py` module.

### 4. Activity SSE stream — no subscriber cleanup on disconnect

[activity.py:112-126](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/activity.py#L112-L126) — [stream()](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/activity.py#112-127) unsubscribes on `CancelledError`, but if the client just drops the TCP connection (common in Docker behind nginx), the `CancelledError` may not fire cleanly. The [add_entry](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/activity.py#52-97) method has a `dead` cleanup for `put_nowait` failures, which helps, but a periodic subscriber prune would be more robust.

### 5. [mcp_client.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/mcp_client.py) — no exponential backoff on reconnect

[ensure_session()](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/mcp_client.py#66-71) just calls [connect()](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/mcp_client.py#27-44) on every failed request. Under rapid failure, this hammers the capsule. Not an issue now but will be under Docker health-check loops.

> **Fix (Phase 4):** Add a backoff timer: `min(2^n, 30)` seconds between reconnect attempts.

### 6. [capsule_manager.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/capsule_manager.py) — no `/api/capsule/restart` route

The [CapsuleManager](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/capsule_manager.py#16-139) has a [restart()](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/self_deploy/backend/capsule_manager.py#118-121) method but [server.py](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/server.py) never exposes it. The Space version also doesn't, but for the standalone this would be useful for debugging.

---

## 🐳 Docker Strategy

This is the main design discussion. There are **three viable architectures** depending on who you're targeting:

---

### Option A: Single-Container (Recommended for v1)

Everything in one container. Simplest for users, mirrors the current HF Space architecture exactly.

```mermaid
graph LR
    subgraph Docker Container
        Backend[FastAPI :7860] --> Capsule[champion_gen8.py :8765]
        Backend --> Frontend[Static Files]
    end
    User[Browser] --> Backend
    IDE[Kiro/Claude/VS Code] -->|/mcp/sse| Backend
    Storage[(data/ volume)] --> Backend
```

#### Dockerfile

```dockerfile
FROM python:3.10-slim

# System deps
RUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \
    curl git && \
    apt-get clean && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*

WORKDIR /app

# Install ALL deps (server + capsule in same container)
COPY requirements.txt requirements-server.txt requirements-capsule.txt ./
RUN pip install --no-cache-dir -r requirements.txt

# Copy application
COPY backend/ backend/
COPY frontend/ frontend/
COPY config/.env.example config/.env.example

# Create data directory
RUN mkdir -p data/brain data/bag data/workflows data/slots data/config

# Capsule goes in at build time or mounted at runtime
# COPY ../capsule/champion_gen8.py capsule/champion_gen8.py
# OR mount: -v /path/to/capsule:/app/capsule

EXPOSE 7860 8765

ENV MANAGE_LOCAL_CAPSULE=1
ENV PERSISTENCE_MODE=local
ENV DATA_DIR=/app/data

CMD ["python", "backend/server.py"]
```

#### docker-compose.yml

```yaml
version: "3.9"
services:
  champion-council:
    build: .
    ports:
      - "7860:7860"     # Web panel
      - "8765:8765"     # MCP SSE (direct capsule access, optional)
    volumes:
      - ./data:/app/data                    # Persistent state
      - ./config/.env:/app/config/.env      # Config (optional)
      # Mount capsule if not baked into image:
      # - ../capsule:/app/capsule
    environment:
      - MANAGE_LOCAL_CAPSULE=1
      - PERSISTENCE_MODE=local
      - APP_PORT=7860
      - MCP_PORT=8765
    restart: unless-stopped
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD", "curl", "-f", "http://localhost:7860/api/health"]
      interval: 30s
      timeout: 10s
      retries: 3
      start_period: 120s   # Capsule needs ~90s to boot
```

**Pros:** Dead simple, one `docker compose up`, matches HF Space 1:1
**Cons:** ~4GB image (torch+jax), can't scale capsule independently

---

### Option B: Two-Container Split (Recommended for v2)

Separate the capsule from the proxy. Allows remote capsule or GPU-specific container.

```mermaid
graph LR
    subgraph proxy-container
        Backend[FastAPI :7860]
        Frontend[Static Files]
    end
    subgraph capsule-container
        Capsule[champion_gen8.py :8765]
    end
    Backend -->|MCP/SSE| Capsule
    User[Browser] --> Backend
    IDE[Kiro/Claude] -->|/mcp/sse| Backend
    ProxyVol[(data/)] --> Backend
    CapsuleVol[(capsule-data/)] --> Capsule
```

```yaml
version: "3.9"
services:
  proxy:
    build:
      context: .
      dockerfile: Dockerfile.proxy
    ports:
      - "7860:7860"
    volumes:
      - ./data:/app/data
    environment:
      - MANAGE_LOCAL_CAPSULE=0
      - MCP_BASE_URL=http://capsule:8765
      - PERSISTENCE_MODE=local
    depends_on:
      capsule:
        condition: service_healthy
    restart: unless-stopped

  capsule:
    build:
      context: .
      dockerfile: Dockerfile.capsule
    ports:
      - "8765:8765"
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD", "curl", "-f", "http://localhost:8765/sse"]
      interval: 10s
      timeout: 5s
      retries: 10
      start_period: 90s
    restart: unless-stopped
```

**Pros:** Proxy image is ~200MB (no ML deps), capsule can run on GPU node, could scale
**Cons:** Two images to manage, networking between containers, more Docker complexity

---

### Option C: Proxy-Only + Remote Capsule

For users who run the capsule on a GPU cloud (Vast/RunPod) but want the panel locally.

```yaml
services:
  panel:
    build:
      context: .
      dockerfile: Dockerfile.proxy
    ports:
      - "7860:7860"
    environment:
      - MANAGE_LOCAL_CAPSULE=0
      - MCP_BASE_URL=https://your-capsule.vast.ai:8765
      - PERSISTENCE_MODE=both
      - HF_TOKEN=${HF_TOKEN}
```

**Pros:** Tiny image, no local GPU needed, connects to existing Vast/HF deployments
**Cons:** Requires external capsule, latency to remote capsule

---

### My Recommendation: Ship Option A now, design for B

Build a **single Dockerfile** that supports all three modes via environment variables. The `MANAGE_LOCAL_CAPSULE=0` + `MCP_BASE_URL` pattern already enables Options B and C without any code changes. You just need different Dockerfiles for the image size optimization.

#### Immediate Deliverables

| File | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| [Dockerfile](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/Dockerfile) | Full single-container (Option A) |
| `Dockerfile.proxy` | Proxy-only, no capsule deps (Options B/C) |
| `docker-compose.yml` | Single-container default |
| `docker-compose.split.yml` | Two-container variant |
| `.dockerignore` | Exclude `.venv`, `data/`, `.git`, `*.vsix`, etc. |

#### Key Docker Design Decisions

1. **Capsule delivery**: Bake [capsule.gz](file:///F:/End-Game/vscode-extension/Champion_Council/capsule/capsule.gz) into the image at build time? Or mount at runtime?
   - **Recommendation:** Mount at runtime via volume. The capsule is 25MB compressed / 35MB uncompressed — not huge, but it changes with each generation. Mounting decouples capsule updates from image rebuilds.

2. **Data persistence**: Docker volume or bind mount?
   - **Recommendation:** Both options in compose file, defaulting to bind mount (`./data:/app/data`) so users can easily inspect/backup state.

3. **Multi-platform builds**: `linux/amd64` + `linux/arm64`?
   - **Recommendation:** `amd64` only for v1 (torch+jax ARM support is spotty). Proxy-only image can do multi-platform.

4. **Image registry**: Where to publish?
   - **Recommendation:** GitHub Container Registry (`ghcr.io/yourusername/champion-council`) — free, integrates with existing GitHub repo.

5. **GPU support**: NVIDIA Container Toolkit for local GPU inference?
   - **Recommendation:** Add `deploy.resources.reservations.devices` section in compose for optional GPU passthrough. Use `nvidia/cuda:12.x-runtime` as base for GPU variant.

